dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:1:{"ts": "2026-07-03T20:52:05.224Z", "seq": 1, "kind": "caveat", "summary": "EXP-S (#2, 0.8.14) coexisting-index / multi-index-write substrate must not foreclose the OPP-12 projection registry that will later sit on it — design the multi-index write so a declarative filterable/rankable/searchable registry can wrap it without a substrate reshape", "area": "engine/substrate", "epistemic": "verified", "id": "TC-1", "owner": "orchestrator", "priority": "p2", "status": "open", "refs": ["opp:OPP-12", "plan:dev/plans/plan-0.8.14.md", "file:dev/design/record-lifecycle-protocol/projection-registry-and-async-embed.md", "git:83ef13fc"], "body": "Grounded caveat for the 0.8.14 EXP-S build (Slice-0 ADR + Slice-5 keystone). OPP-12's engine-owned projection registry (filterable/rankable/searchable declarations; same-txn FTS/filter, async vector via the existing worker + the atomic dense_readiness flip) is architecturally a DECLARATIVE FRONT-END over exactly the coexisting-index / incremental multi-index write that EXP-S builds -- EXP-S is the substrate the projection registry will sit on (OPP-12 lands >=0.9.x). No dependency edge forces ordering, and EXP-S touches NONE of OPP-12's surface (verified: plan-0.8.14 has no SearchHit / lifecycle / projection scope). But the Slice-0 substrate ADR should design the multi-index write so a later projection registry can WRAP it without a substrate reshape (don't foreclose per-kind declarative projection specs or the async-vector dense_readiness flip). Re-check at OPP-12 scheduling. See [[opp12-record-lifecycle-protocol]]."}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:3:{"ts": "2026-07-04T00:19:41.019Z", "seq": 3, "kind": "caveat", "summary": "DESIGN-ADDRESSED: the 0.8.14 Slice-0 ADR (dff4830c, D5) DISCHARGES this caveat — the D2 per-kind index-target set is the seam a later OPP-12 projection registry wraps; FTS/filter same-txn + vector async-via-worker preserved; terminal-cursor readiness kept per-kind-extensible. Now WATCHING: re-check the Slice-5 keystone actually honors the seam, and again at OPP-12 scheduling", "area": "engine/substrate", "epistemic": "verified", "id": "TC-1", "owner": "orchestrator", "priority": "p2", "status": "watching", "refs": ["seq:1", "git:dff4830c", "opp:OPP-12"], "body": "Advanced from open->watching. The ratified Slice-0 substrate ADR explicitly discharges TC-1 in §D5 (verified from git dff4830c): the engine already owns the async substrate a future OPP-12 projection registry needs (projection workers + _fathomdb_projection_terminal readiness = durable dense_readiness equivalent; per-kind kind_is_vector_indexed), and the ADR obligates EXP-S to (a) keep the D2 per-kind index-target set a wrappable seam, (b) preserve FTS/filter same-txn + vector async-via-worker (no collapse to sync), (c) keep terminal-cursor readiness per-kind-extensible. Trigger to re-check: the Slice-5 keystone implementation honors these; then close/re-open at OPP-12 scheduling (>=0.9.x)."}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:4:{"ts": "2026-07-04T01:29:26.727Z", "seq": 4, "kind": "consideration", "summary": "Engine::bm25f_search scores by re-tokenizing each field via a temp-FTS5 round-trip (fts5_tokenize) per field/candidate — correctness-first, but there is NO perf gate on bm25f_search. A future perf pass / Slice 40 / the 1-2M scaling work should weigh this before F5 rides a hot path", "area": "engine/fts-bm25f", "epistemic": "verified", "id": "TC-3", "owner": "hitl", "priority": "p3", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:c57e4e99", "plan:dev/plans/plan-0.8.14.md"], "body": "Surfaced at 0.8.14 Slice 10 (F5 BM25F, c57e4e99); flagged by BOTH codex §9 and the implementer. The in-engine BM25F scorer (justified ADR-0.8.1 deviation — FTS5 bm25() pins k1/b, so scoring is done in-engine to honor R-F5-1's tunable b) computes per-field term stats by re-tokenizing each field through fts5_tokenize per field per candidate. Correct + tokenization-faithful (the fix-1 that resolved codex's medium finding), but O(fields x candidates) tokenizer round-trips with no perf gate on the path. Engine-internal / experimental today, so NOT blocking. Re-weigh before F5 is put on a hot/large query path: a perf gate at Slice 40 (release readiness) or during the 1-2M scaling work, or a caching/precompute optimization. Ref c57e4e99 (bm25f_search)."}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:7:{"ts": "2026-07-06T01:25:40.538Z", "seq": 7, "kind": "todo", "summary": "Re-baseline the eu7 0.90 recall floor for the GROWN 18,472-doc cross-source corpus. The floor + the 0.896 CPU baseline (ci_hi 0.925) predate the musique (Jun 16) + compmix (Jul 3) cross-source additions, which mechanically lower recall@10 at fixed N. Needs a fresh CPU same-backend eu7 N=7667 measurement on the current corpus + an HITL threshold ruling on a corpus-appropriate floor. Separate from 0.8.14 (D6 zero vec0 rewrite excludes a regression)", "area": "eval/eu7", "epistemic": "verified", "id": "TC-5", "owner": "hitl", "priority": "p1", "status": "open", "refs": ["file:dev/design/gpu-eval-activities-policy.md", "plan:dev/plans/plan-0.8.14.md"], "body": "Surfaced at 0.8.14 Slice 20: a GPU eu7 run read vector-stage recall@10 N=7667=0.833 (ci_hi 0.864 < 0.90) vs the historical CPU baseline 0.896 (ci_hi 0.925 PASS); N=1000=0.950 PASS. Two verified confounds: (1) cross-backend (GPU embed vs CPU baseline; near-threshold 1-bit-quant flips at large N) -- fixed forward: eu7/fidelity gates now run CPU same-backend per gpu-eval-activities-policy.md; (2) corpus growth (musique+compmix added post-baseline). D6 (codex-verified zero vec0 rewrite @ Slice 5) excludes a 0.8.14 regression, so Slice 20 closed on the D6 no-op basis (HITL). OPEN: is 0.90 still right for the grown corpus? Resolve via a fresh CPU same-backend eu7 N=7667 on the current corpus, then an HITL floor ruling (keep 0.90 or re-baseline). Placement TBD."}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:9:{"ts": "2026-07-08T00:18:18.773Z", "seq": 9, "kind": "consideration", "summary": "C-1 co-design TIMING (EntityTypeSpec -> ProjectionSpec): Memex's Commission C / entity-schema-registry is its ACTUAL 0.5.x work and is LIVE NOW; it builds toward the C-1 seam. C-1 is HARD (one declarative registration flow -- app never syncs two registries). FathomDB's projection registry is 0.9.1, but the EntityTypeSpec->ProjectionSpec co-design ADR should be AGREED before Memex locks Commission C's registry shape, or we recreate the two-registry-sync drift C-1 exists to prevent. Near-term cross-repo coordination watch (raise to HITL) even though the FathomDB build is >=0.9.x.", "area": "cross-repo/co-design", "epistemic": "verified", "id": "TC-7", "owner": "hitl", "priority": "p1", "status": "open", "refs": ["opp:OPP-12", "file:dev/plans/0.9.x-roadmap-DRAFT.md", "git:6f7456c"]}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:15:{"ts": "2026-07-08T03:14:33.179Z", "seq": 15, "kind": "reconcile", "summary": "TC-7 SLOT CORRECTION (stays RESOLVED): the C-1 EntityTypeSpec->ProjectionSpec co-land is NO LONGER '0.9.1 P2.S-F'. Per master F-19/F-20 (and OPP-12 sub-ledger seq 8) C-1 co-lands at FathomDB 0.8.20 (OPP-12 Phase-2 + breaking-pair publish), DESIGN UNCHANGED. Read every '0.9.1'/'P2.S-F' in seq 13 + the converged contract as 0.8.20. No re-ratification (scheduling change, not contract change).", "area": "cross-repo/co-design", "epistemic": "verified", "id": "TC-7", "owner": "hitl", "priority": "p1", "status": "resolved", "refs": ["file:dev/design/record-lifecycle-protocol/OPP-12-C1-converged-contract.md", "opp:OPP-12", "seq:13", "git:f3ccf67a"]}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:18:{"ts": "2026-07-09T12:27:12.326Z", "seq": 18, "kind": "todo", "summary": "TC-9 EXTENSION (D3/L3 finding, 2026-07-09, Steward-verified): ONNX-GPU-EP cross-backend Delta measured OOB (durable doc git:76568975). candle-CPU(Cls) <-> ONNX-CUDA-EP(Cls; ORT 1.26.0 GPU + cuDNN 9.5 + RTX3090 cuda:1) = 2/17280 raw sign flips (1/17280 proxy-mean-centered), cosine 0.99999996, L2 <= 5.4e-4, deterministic x3, EFFECTIVE PROVIDER VERIFIED CUDA -- the FIRST non-byte-identical cross-backend leg (both prior CPU legs = 0 flips; pure GPU FP divergence, not a broken export). FINDING: as-shipped OrtBgeEmbedder under ort=2.0.0-rc.10 (default-features=false) CANNOT instantiate the CUDA EP -- ort::init() is never called (Steward-verified ABSENT in ort_bge.rs; the EP-dispatch + loud-fallback code IS present) -> ORT 'DefaultLogger not registered' -> LOUD CPU fallback. Proven binding-not-host: same native stack runs CUDA via Python + via a standalone rc.10 probe WITH a one-time ort::init().commit(). NOT a shipped hazard (ONNX = opt-in non-default EVAL feature; fallback is LOUD not silent; default library path = candle-CPU, unaffected). ACTION folded into TC-9 (ort 2.0-stable bump): (a) add a one-time ORT env init so ONNX GPU/cross-vendor EPs are reachable, (b) re-verify CUDA-EP session creation on 2.0-stable. #5/D4 BEARING: none now -- the D4 same-identity floor stays tight (0 flips; same-identity candle CPU<->CUDA was 0/6144 @0.8.7), and the 2-flip GPU-EP leg is a DISTINCT '-onnx' identity already refused by identity + R-VEQ-5 additive-only; a FUTURE cross-vendor portability ADR must budget a NON-ZERO GPU-EP flip rate.", "decider": "steward", "extends": "TC-9", "refs": ["git:76568975", "file:dev/plans/runs/0.8.18-slice-0-onnx-gpu-ep-calibration.md", "file:src/rust/crates/fathomdb-embedder/src/ort_bge.rs"]}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:19:{"ts": "2026-07-09T18:27:35.304Z", "seq": 19, "kind": "todo", "summary": "TC-10 (NEW, HITL-directed 2026-07-09): #5 vector-equivalence probe OPEN-LATENCY. The #5 keystone re-embeds the 45-probe set at EVERY open of a vector-kind DB (the cross-open backend-drift check) -> a new OPEN-time overhead. NOT a query-latency / AC-012/013/020 breach (the read path adds only an open-time AtomicBool dense_disabled check; representation unchanged). ACTION: (a) MEASURE the open-latency overhead (45 CPU embeds at open); (b) consider IDENTITY-GATED probe caching -- re-run the probe only when the embedder identity/revision CHANGES since last open, not every open (the EmbedderIdentity pre-filter already tracks identity) -- as a future-micro optimization; (c) optionally a GA open-latency AC/measured note. Surfaced at 0.8.18 Slice-40 GA verification (orchestrator); HITL directed TC-track, NOT a GA blocker (0.8.18 closed label-only). Owner: future micro (convenient slot >=0.8.21 or fold into an OPP-12 slice). Correctness-first: the every-open probe is correct; caching is an optimization.", "decider": "hitl", "kind_detail": "open-latency", "release": "0.8.18", "refs": ["file:dev/design/0.8.18-slice-0-vector-equivalence-publish-design.md"]}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:25:{"ts": "2026-07-19T03:35:38.066Z", "seq": 25, "kind": "observation", "summary": "eu7 is a CPU SAME-BACKEND gate: a GPU-run eu7 number is NOT comparable to the 0.90 floor and manufactures a FALSE REGRESSION. Verified at 0.8.20 Slice-0 from run artifacts: CPU (GA-signoff-eu7-remeasure-20260608T172804Z.json) n=7667 vector-stage recall@10 = 0.8960 CI [0.8640, 0.9250] => PASS on the one-sided gate (ci_hi >= 0.90). GPU (dev/plans/runs/0.8.14-slice-20-eu7-gpu-run-20260705T205222Z.log:73) n=7667 = 0.8330 CI [0.8010, 0.8640] => FAIL. The delta is a cross-backend quantization artifact, NOT a code regression (it is the TC-5 floor re-baseline driver, scheduled 0.8.23). CONSEQUENCE: the standing HITL GPU-eval mandate (repo-must-use-gpu-for-eval-when-3090-room) DOES NOT APPLY to the eu7 recall gate -- by that mandate's own 'fidelity-safe' caveat. Any release taking an eu7 basis decision (0.8.20 R-20-EU7 at Slice 40; TC-5 at 0.8.23) MUST capture and compare on CPU only, and must compare against a CPU reference. Running eu7 on the 3090s to 'honor the mandate' would wrongly force a re-baseline.", "cx": "TC-12", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "0", "status": "OPEN", "refs": ["file:dev/design/0.8.20-slice0-erasure-design.md#8", "file:dev/plans/runs/STATUS-0.8.20.md#6", "seq:24"]}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:32:{"ts": "2026-07-19T04:09:21.079Z", "seq": 32, "kind": "observation", "summary": "ROOT CAUSE: the eu7 harness CANNOT COMPLETE ON CPU on this box -- BATCH=256 exceeds its own hardcoded 600s drain timeout at the measured embed rate. Measured at 4ca70ba6 by bisecting N (three runs): n=7667 FAILED, n=200 FAILED, n=20 PASSED. All three failures are identical: panic at eu7_real_corpus_ac.rs:414 'seed drain (batch): Scheduler' == engine.drain(600_000) -> wait_for_idle timed out -> EngineError::Scheduler. THE WORKER IS NOT WEDGED: n=20 passed cleanly (exit 0, vector_stage recall@10 = 1.0000, 258.54s) so the embed/projection path is FUNCTIONALLY CORRECT. It is THROUGHPUT. The n=20 run reports seed_ms=111670 for 20 docs = 0.179 docs/sec, which is ~7.3x SLOWER than the 1.3 docs/sec the harness docstring assumes (:97-99). At 0.179 docs/s a BATCH of 256 needs ~1430s, so it can NEVER drain inside the hardcoded 600_000 ms -- the harness is STRUCTURALLY unable to run here regardless of N, because failure happens on the FIRST batch. Full 7667-doc seed would need ~11.9 HOURS even if the timeout were raised. NOT a weights problem (cache complete: config.json + tokenizer.json + model.safetensors present) and not CPU contention (load 4.5 of 24 cores). OPTIONS for Slice 40: (a) reduce BATCH 256 -> 64 (64/0.179 = 358s, fits inside 600s) or make BATCH/timeout env-tunable -- minimal, surgical, does NOT change measurement semantics; (b) raise the drain timeout and accept a ~12h CPU run; (c) investigate the 7x throughput shortfall vs the documented rate, which may itself be a real CPU-embed regression worth catching. RECOMMEND (a)+(c). NOTE THE TENSION: TC-12 forbids running eu7 on GPU for comparability, and CPU cannot finish -- so R-20-EU7 has NO runnable path until this is fixed. Slice 40 must not treat this as optional. SIDE-EFFECT HAZARD: the harness WRITES dev/plans/runs/eu7-latest-measurements.json into the repo on every run, so a reduced-N scouting run silently produces a file that LOOKS authoritative (the n=20 run wrote recall=1.0000 there). Do not commit it from a scouting run.", "cx": "TC-19", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "40", "status": "OPEN", "refs": ["file:src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/eu7_real_corpus_ac.rs", "seq:26"]}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:45:{"ts": "2026-07-20T02:14:53.190Z", "seq": 45, "kind": "observation", "summary": "WRITE/READ PROVENANCE ASYMMETRY -- the 'NO SDK EXPOSURE' erasure gap, now measured. 0.8.20 makes provenance structurally MANDATORY on write (SourceId newtype), but PySearchHit.source_id is populated ONLY for graph-arm hits and is None for every two-arm (text/vector) hit -- documented at src/rust/crates/fathomdb-py/src/lib.rs:537-539. So a caller can be forced to supply provenance yet cannot read it back on an ordinary search hit. Measured consequence: BOTH remaining Python suite failures (test_option2_elps_pipeline::test_build_fathomdb_elps_path_uses_ingest_with_extractor and test_verify_embed_db::test_complete_embed_is_queryable) are caused by this -- _doc_id_of falls through the 'if sid:' branch because source_id is None, reaching int(sh.id) which has raised TypeError since 0.8.19 made SearchHit.id an IdSpace (C-2). ONE read-side fix (expose source_id on all arms) likely closes BOTH. Verified pre-existing: identical failures on origin/main f22e4947 in an isolated A/B clone; _doc_id_of is byte-identical on main.", "id": "TC-31", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "5", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:9c87d758"]}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:50:{"ts": "2026-07-20T18:15:47.518Z", "seq": 50, "kind": "observation", "summary": "TC-31 RESOLVED — source_id readable on every search-hit path (Py+TS), erase_source round-trip closed", "id": "TC-31", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "10", "status": "resolved", "refs": ["git:93a57b10", "plan:dev/plans/plan-0.8.20.md"], "body": "Engine populated source_id at the 5 caller-reachable SearchHit sites (vector node, vector edge_fact, text/BM25F, pre-step-12 legacy text tiered, edge FTS) by adding one column to an existing SELECT/JOIN — no N+1 (there is no index on canonical_nodes(write_cursor)). Node hits carry canonical_nodes.source_id; edge hits carry canonical_edges.source_id; graph-arm semantics unchanged. rerank_passages left None deliberately: pure fn, no DB handle, hit never escapes to a caller — populating would fabricate provenance. Verified by execution in fresh clones: Python 787 passed/12 skipped, TS 186/186. codex §9 terminal PASS."}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:57:{"ts": "2026-07-20T20:08:58.363Z", "seq": 57, "kind": "observation", "summary": "search is NOT one of the five read verbs — every ReadView visibility axis must be separately applied to Engine::search or it leaks", "id": "TC-38", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "15", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:ab790880"], "body": "MEASURED by codex §9 on Slice 15b. Slice 10 scoped ReadView to FIVE read verbs (read_get, read_get_many, read_list, read_list_filter, graph_neighbors). Engine::search is NOT among them: read_search_in_tx hydrates hits from search_index/vector rows using ONLY 'superseded_at IS NULL AND state = active', with no validity predicate. This was LATENT and unreachable while no SDK caller could author a validity window; TC-34 (Slice 15b) made authoring reachable from Py/TS and thereby turned it into a LIVE defect — an SDK-authored out-of-window node still came back from search while read_get/read_list correctly hid it. Note dev/design/record-lifecycle-protocol/api-surface.md:50 always specified ReadView on 'search' too, so the five-verb scope was a narrowing, not the contract. THE DURABLE LESSON, which outlives this fix: the five-read-verb ReadView plumbing and the search path are SEPARATE code paths, so ANY future visibility axis (a new relax-flag, a new lifecycle state, a new temporal dimension) added to ReadView will silently NOT apply to search unless separately wired. Slices 20 and 25 and any later release adding a visibility axis must check both. A search-based test CANNOT catch this class — assert on the read verbs AND on search."}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:59:{"ts": "2026-07-20T20:09:31.141Z", "seq": 59, "kind": "consideration", "summary": "R-20-PR registry shape: plan's roles:{filterable,rankable,searchable} as three booleans CANNOT express the ratified C-1 contract — must be a SET of typed roles", "id": "TC-40", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "15", "status": "open", "refs": ["plan:dev/design/record-lifecycle-protocol/OPP-12-C1-converged-contract.md"], "body": "ORCHESTRATOR DESIGN FINDING, code-grounded, for whoever builds R-20-PR/R-20-EAV. plan-0.8.20.md §1/§3 summarises the registry as 'ProjectionSpec {name, roles: {filterable, rankable, searchable}}'. Read as three booleans that is UNBUILDABLE against the RATIFIED C-1 contract, for three independent reasons. (1) C-1 Q4's whole tiering mechanism is 'declare the cheap roles now, ADD the vector role at promote(), drop on reject' — that REQUIRES searchable->FTS and searchable->vector to be SEPARATELY declarable; one 'searchable' boolean cannot express it. (2) The staleness contract (projection-registry-and-async-embed.md §3) splits them by guarantee: filterable + searchable->FTS are SAME-TRANSACTION, searchable->vector is ASYNC carrying dense_readiness. (3) Slice 20 (R-20-DR, dense_readiness + atomic flip) attaches ONLY to searchable->vector — a boolean gives Slice 20 nothing to attach to. C-1 Q1 also fixes the wire shape: Memex ALREADY LANDED 'AttributeSpec.index: Set[ProjectionRole]' inert at memex 95ed450, so the engine must accept a SET or the ratified cross-repo seam does not connect. Recommended: enum ProjectionRole { Filterable, SearchableFts{tokenizer:Option<String>}, SearchableVector{embedder:Option<String>}, Rankable } with roles as a set; absent tokenizer/embedder => engine default (C-1 'Tokenizer/embedder defaults' section). This matters beyond Slice 15 because Slice 30's RUBRIC-H7 can-i-deploy gate mechanically checks as-built code against OPP-12-C1-converged-contract.md — a three-boolean shape would FAIL Slice 30 and HOLD the breaking pair."}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:60:{"ts": "2026-07-20T20:09:31.164Z", "seq": 60, "kind": "consideration", "summary": "R-20-PR: 'filterable' has TWO incompatible backends — vec0 pre-KNN filtering cannot be extended without a full re-embed; ADR-0.8.11 D3 forbids the post-KNN fallback", "id": "TC-41", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "15", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:29eba153"], "body": "ORCHESTRATOR DESIGN FINDING, code-grounded. The 'filterable' role resolves to storage through TWO different, incompatible engines today. (A) SEARCH/vector backend: vector_filter_clause (engine lib.rs:8685-8710) is a HARDCODED four-column map onto vec0 metadata columns {source_type, kind, created_at, status}. vec0 is a virtual table with NO ALTER, so adding a fifth filterable field on the pre-KNN path means DROP+RECREATE vector_default and RE-EMBED THE WHOLE CORPUS — per registration. Unacceptable. (B) read.list backend: Predicate::to_sql_clause emits json_extract(body, path) gated by the COMPILE-TIME const PREDICATE_PATH_ALLOWLIST (lib.rs:1808) of exactly six paths. The obvious escape — join EAV after the KNN — is EXPLICITLY FORBIDDEN by ADR-0.8.11 D3 no-demotion, which is enforced in the type system: a Json filter term is TYPE-REJECTED on the vector backend (lib.rs:2038-2044). So all three options are constrained and the tension is REAL, not incidental. NOTE the C-1 contract describes filterable as a 'pre-KNN constraint' (projection-registry-and-async-embed.md §2), i.e. backend (A) — the expensive one. ORCHESTRATOR RECOMMENDATION (NOT ratified, owed to the HITL): scope filterable to backend (B) for 0.8.20 — the registry supersedes the compile-time PREDICATE_PATH_ALLOWLIST with a runtime-registered set, and the vec0 metadata filter set stays FROZEN at its four columns. This is a DEVIATION from the contract's pre-KNN wording and must be ratified, not assumed, because Slice 30's H7 can-i-deploy gate checks as-built against that contract."}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:61:{"ts": "2026-07-20T20:09:58.062Z", "seq": 61, "kind": "open_question", "summary": "TC-33 migration story worked out: node/edge temporal split CONFIRMS the INTEGER recommendation; blast radius is small in schema but crosses an external BYO-LLM wire format", "id": "TC-33", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "15", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:29eba153"], "body": "ORCHESTRATOR DESIGN WORK on the HITL-directed harmonisation. CONCLUSION: converge on INTEGER epoch seconds, i.e. the Steward recommendation STANDS — no escalation of the direction call is required on the merits. SCHEMA BLAST RADIUS IS SMALLER THAN FEARED: exactly ONE table, TWO columns (canonical_edges.t_valid/t_invalid, TEXT, added by step 14), and ZERO indexes reference either column, so no index rebuild is forced. BUT the real cost is NOT the schema, it is FIVE surfaces: (1) 8 SQL predicate sites that today inline datetime('now') (engine lib.rs:7806, 9553, 9685, 10074, 10112, 10903, 10970, 4539) must switch to a BOUND :now — which is a strict improvement, it is what makes edge validity deterministically testable the way node validity already is; (2) PreparedWrite::Edge t_valid/t_invalid Option<String> -> Option<i64>, a breaking binding-coordination change; (3) ConsolidateCandidateEdge AND its harness JSON contract (lib.rs:4405-4406) which is an EXTERNAL BYO-LLM wire format; (4) temporal_fallback is derived by STRING EQUALITY comparing t_valid against warnings[].substituted_t_valid (lib.rs:4302-4305, 4123-4141) and BREAKS SILENTLY under a type change — this is the sharpest edge and needs its own RED test; (5) two tests that deliberately PIN the TEXT representation (s22_edge_temporal_columns_are_untouched_text in schema/tests/step22_migration.rs:211, r_20_nv_edge_temporal_filter_is_unchanged in engine/tests/slice10_node_validity.rs:624) must be rewritten, not deleted — they were the drift guard and must be replaced by an INTEGER equivalent. LAYERING CALL OWED TO THE HITL: storage and the governed SDK surface should both become INTEGER, but the BYO-LLM EXTRACTOR JSON should KEEP ISO-8601 with engine-side normalisation on ingest — an LLM cannot reliably emit epoch seconds, and that boundary already has a normalisation layer. This is a layering boundary, not splitting the difference on the representation; flagging it explicitly because it is adjacent enough to the direction call that the HITL should confirm it. MIGRATION MECHANICS: SQLite has no ALTER COLUMN TYPE, and the pinning test asserts declared type == TEXT, so true harmonisation requires a 12-step TABLE REBUILD of canonical_edges (create-new / copy-with-conversion / drop / rename), not an UPDATE in place. HAZARD: strftime('%s', x) returns NULL on an unparseable value, and a NULL t_invalid READS AS 'still valid' — so a junk value silently RESURRECTS an invalidated edge. That must be a RED test and a migration-time hard failure, never a silent NULL. SCHEDULING NOTE: this needs schema step 24 (23 being the EAV/registry step), making FOUR migrations in 0.8.20. I-6 'one migration per release' is GUIDANCE, not enforced — there is no test counting steps per release, and 0.8.20 already ships two (21 and 22), which dev/plans/0.8.6-0.8.16-PROGRAM-SEQUENCING.md:417 explicitly blesses. So four is precedented but should be surfaced, not slipped through."}
dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:62:{"ts": "2026-07-20T21:35:56.822Z", "seq": 62, "kind": "observation", "summary": "GATE-INTEGRITY: R-20-NV was closed at Slice 10 while one of its three Slice-0-named RED tests (valid_as_of_binds_now_once) was NEVER WRITTEN — and that exact property then regressed", "id": "TC-42", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "15", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:a8087dfb"], "body": "MEASURED, and the failure it predicted actually happened. dev/design/0.8.20-slice0-erasure-design.md:308 names THREE falsifiable RED tests for R-20-NV: validity_window_matrix, valid_as_of_binds_now_once, crossed_boundary_since_hook. A grep across src/ finds ZERO hits for valid_as_of_binds_now_once — it exists ONLY in that design table. R-20-NV was nevertheless declared CLOSED at Slice 10. The property it was supposed to pin (':now' binds ONCE PER QUERY, not per row/arm — a per-arm bind makes results non-deterministic across a validity boundary) then REGRESSED in Slice 15b fix-2, where the graph arm re-read current_epoch_seconds independently of the instant already resolved for the text/vector arms. codex §9 caught it; the never-written test would have caught it first. TWO DURABLE CONSEQUENCES. (1) TRACEABILITY IS UNENFORCED: a Slice-0 design can name a RED test, the slice can close without writing it, and nothing detects the gap — the acceptance table is prose, not a gate. Slice 40's DoD should mechanically check that every test NAMED in the Slice-0 acceptance tables actually EXISTS in src/, for every requirement, not just this one. Other named-but-unverified tests may exist across R-20-RV/PR/EAV/DR/SUR — this was found by accident, so assume it is not the only one. (2) NAMING: the property is now pinned for the first time by default_view_search_reads_the_clock_once_per_query (Slice 15b fix-3), which does NOT match the design's name. Either rename it or cross-reference it, or a traceability sweep will still report R-20-NV as missing a test."}
