dev/plans/runs/codex/0.8.20/slice-15-steward-positions-verify-20260721T041028Z.log:2800:dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:57:{"ts": "2026-07-20T20:08:58.363Z", "seq": 57, "kind": "observation", "summary": "search is NOT one of the five read verbs — every ReadView visibility axis must be separately applied to Engine::search or it leaks", "id": "TC-38", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "15", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:ab790880"], "body": "MEASURED by codex §9 on Slice 15b. Slice 10 scoped ReadView to FIVE read verbs (read_get, read_get_many, read_list, read_list_filter, graph_neighbors). Engine::search is NOT among them: read_search_in_tx hydrates hits from search_index/vector rows using ONLY 'superseded_at IS NULL AND state = active', with no validity predicate. This was LATENT and unreachable while no SDK caller could author a validity window; TC-34 (Slice 15b) made authoring reachable from Py/TS and thereby turned it into a LIVE defect — an SDK-authored out-of-window node still came back from search while read_get/read_list correctly hid it. Note dev/design/record-lifecycle-protocol/api-surface.md:50 always specified ReadView on 'search' too, so the five-verb scope was a narrowing, not the contract. THE DURABLE LESSON, which outlives this fix: the five-read-verb ReadView plumbing and the search path are SEPARATE code paths, so ANY future visibility axis (a new relax-flag, a new lifecycle state, a new temporal dimension) added to ReadView will silently NOT apply to search unless separately wired. Slices 20 and 25 and any later release adding a visibility axis must check both. A search-based test CANNOT catch this class — assert on the read verbs AND on search."}
dev/plans/runs/codex/0.8.20/slice-15-steward-positions-verify-20260721T041028Z.log:2801:dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:59:{"ts": "2026-07-20T20:09:31.141Z", "seq": 59, "kind": "consideration", "summary": "R-20-PR registry shape: plan's roles:{filterable,rankable,searchable} as three booleans CANNOT express the ratified C-1 contract — must be a SET of typed roles", "id": "TC-40", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "15", "status": "open", "refs": ["plan:dev/design/record-lifecycle-protocol/OPP-12-C1-converged-contract.md"], "body": "ORCHESTRATOR DESIGN FINDING, code-grounded, for whoever builds R-20-PR/R-20-EAV. plan-0.8.20.md §1/§3 summarises the registry as 'ProjectionSpec {name, roles: {filterable, rankable, searchable}}'. Read as three booleans that is UNBUILDABLE against the RATIFIED C-1 contract, for three independent reasons. (1) C-1 Q4's whole tiering mechanism is 'declare the cheap roles now, ADD the vector role at promote(), drop on reject' — that REQUIRES searchable->FTS and searchable->vector to be SEPARATELY declarable; one 'searchable' boolean cannot express it. (2) The staleness contract (projection-registry-and-async-embed.md §3) splits them by guarantee: filterable + searchable->FTS are SAME-TRANSACTION, searchable->vector is ASYNC carrying dense_readiness. (3) Slice 20 (R-20-DR, dense_readiness + atomic flip) attaches ONLY to searchable->vector — a boolean gives Slice 20 nothing to attach to. C-1 Q1 also fixes the wire shape: Memex ALREADY LANDED 'AttributeSpec.index: Set[ProjectionRole]' inert at memex 95ed450, so the engine must accept a SET or the ratified cross-repo seam does not connect. Recommended: enum ProjectionRole { Filterable, SearchableFts{tokenizer:Option<String>}, SearchableVector{embedder:Option<String>}, Rankable } with roles as a set; absent tokenizer/embedder => engine default (C-1 'Tokenizer/embedder defaults' section). This matters beyond Slice 15 because Slice 30's RUBRIC-H7 can-i-deploy gate mechanically checks as-built code against OPP-12-C1-converged-contract.md — a three-boolean shape would FAIL Slice 30 and HOLD the breaking pair."}
dev/plans/runs/codex/0.8.20/slice-15-steward-positions-verify-20260721T041028Z.log:2802:dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:60:{"ts": "2026-07-20T20:09:31.164Z", "seq": 60, "kind": "consideration", "summary": "R-20-PR: 'filterable' has TWO incompatible backends — vec0 pre-KNN filtering cannot be extended without a full re-embed; ADR-0.8.11 D3 forbids the post-KNN fallback", "id": "TC-41", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "15", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:29eba153"], "body": "ORCHESTRATOR DESIGN FINDING, code-grounded. The 'filterable' role resolves to storage through TWO different, incompatible engines today. (A) SEARCH/vector backend: vector_filter_clause (engine lib.rs:8685-8710) is a HARDCODED four-column map onto vec0 metadata columns {source_type, kind, created_at, status}. vec0 is a virtual table with NO ALTER, so adding a fifth filterable field on the pre-KNN path means DROP+RECREATE vector_default and RE-EMBED THE WHOLE CORPUS — per registration. Unacceptable. (B) read.list backend: Predicate::to_sql_clause emits json_extract(body, path) gated by the COMPILE-TIME const PREDICATE_PATH_ALLOWLIST (lib.rs:1808) of exactly six paths. The obvious escape — join EAV after the KNN — is EXPLICITLY FORBIDDEN by ADR-0.8.11 D3 no-demotion, which is enforced in the type system: a Json filter term is TYPE-REJECTED on the vector backend (lib.rs:2038-2044). So all three options are constrained and the tension is REAL, not incidental. NOTE the C-1 contract describes filterable as a 'pre-KNN constraint' (projection-registry-and-async-embed.md §2), i.e. backend (A) — the expensive one. ORCHESTRATOR RECOMMENDATION (NOT ratified, owed to the HITL): scope filterable to backend (B) for 0.8.20 — the registry supersedes the compile-time PREDICATE_PATH_ALLOWLIST with a runtime-registered set, and the vec0 metadata filter set stays FROZEN at its four columns. This is a DEVIATION from the contract's pre-KNN wording and must be ratified, not assumed, because Slice 30's H7 can-i-deploy gate checks as-built against that contract."}
dev/plans/runs/codex/0.8.20/slice-15-steward-positions-verify-20260721T041028Z.log:2803:dev/todos-and-considerations-ledger.jsonl:61:{"ts": "2026-07-20T20:09:58.062Z", "seq": 61, "kind": "open_question", "summary": "TC-33 migration story worked out: node/edge temporal split CONFIRMS the INTEGER recommendation; blast radius is small in schema but crosses an external BYO-LLM wire format", "id": "TC-33", "release": "0.8.20", "slice": "15", "status": "open", "refs": ["git:29eba153"], "body": "ORCHESTRATOR DESIGN WORK on the HITL-directed harmonisation. CONCLUSION: converge on INTEGER epoch seconds, i.e. the Steward recommendation STANDS — no escalation of the direction call is required on the merits. SCHEMA BLAST RADIUS IS SMALLER THAN FEARED: exactly ONE table, TWO columns (canonical_edges.t_valid/t_invalid, TEXT, added by step 14), and ZERO indexes reference either column, so no index rebuild is forced. BUT the real cost is NOT the schema, it is FIVE surfaces: (1) 8 SQL predicate sites that today inline datetime('now') (engine lib.rs:7806, 9553, 9685, 10074, 10112, 10903, 10970, 4539) must switch to a BOUND :now — which is a strict improvement, it is what makes edge validity deterministically testable the way node validity already is; (2) PreparedWrite::Edge t_valid/t_invalid Option<String> -> Option<i64>, a breaking binding-coordination change; (3) ConsolidateCandidateEdge AND its harness JSON contract (lib.rs:4405-4406) which is an EXTERNAL BYO-LLM wire format; (4) temporal_fallback is derived by STRING EQUALITY comparing t_valid against warnings[].substituted_t_valid (lib.rs:4302-4305, 4123-4141) and BREAKS SILENTLY under a type change — this is the sharpest edge and needs its own RED test; (5) two tests that deliberately PIN the TEXT representation (s22_edge_temporal_columns_are_untouched_text in schema/tests/step22_migration.rs:211, r_20_nv_edge_temporal_filter_is_unchanged in engine/tests/slice10_node_validity.rs:624) must be rewritten, not deleted — they were the drift guard and must be replaced by an INTEGER equivalent. LAYERING CALL OWED TO THE HITL: storage and the governed SDK surface should both become INTEGER, but the BYO-LLM EXTRACTOR JSON should KEEP ISO-8601 with engine-side normalisation on ingest — an LLM cannot reliably emit epoch seconds, and that boundary already has a normalisation layer. This is a layering boundary, not splitting the difference on the representation; flagging it explicitly because it is adjacent enough to the direction call that the HITL should confirm it. MIGRATION MECHANICS: SQLite has no ALTER COLUMN TYPE, and the pinning test asserts declared type == TEXT, so true harmonisation requires a 12-step TABLE REBUILD of canonical_edges (create-new / copy-with-conversion / drop / rename), not an UPDATE in place. HAZARD: strftime('%s', x) returns NULL on an unparseable value, and a NULL t_invalid READS AS 'still valid' — so a junk value silently RESURRECTS an invalidated edge. That must be a RED test and a migration-time hard failure, never a silent NULL. SCHEDULING NOTE: this needs schema step 24 (23 being the EAV/registry step), making FOUR migrations in 0.8.20. I-6 'one migration per release' is GUIDANCE, not enforced — there is no test counting steps per release, and 0.8.20 already ships two (21 and 22), which dev/plans/0.8.6-0.8.16-PROGRAM-SEQUENCING.md:417 explicitly blesses. So four is precedented but should be surfaced, not slipped through."}
