**P1: CONFIRMED, with one wire caveat.**

Steward is right. The ratified C-1 contract defines `ProjectionRole ∈ {filterable, rankable, searchable}` and `roles: Set<ProjectionRole>`; `fts` / `vector` are optional sub-objects selecting the searchable target, not additional roles. Evidence: [api-surface.md](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/dev/design/record-lifecycle-protocol/api-surface.md:85), [OPP-12-C1-shot1.md](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/dev/design/record-lifecycle-protocol/OPP-12-C1-shot1.md:12), [OPP-12-C1-converged-contract.md](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/dev/design/record-lifecycle-protocol/OPP-12-C1-converged-contract.md:20). Q4 uses `searchable→FTS` / `searchable→vector` as tier labels, but not enum roles: [OPP-12-C1-converged-contract.md](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/dev/design/record-lifecycle-protocol/OPP-12-C1-converged-contract.md:54).

The plan is stale/narrow: it says `ProjectionSpec {name, roles: {filterable, rankable, searchable}}` and omits `fts?: { tokenizer }` / `vector?: { embedder }`: [plan-0.8.20.md](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/dev/plans/plan-0.8.20.md:72). The real fix is additive: add those sub-objects.

Wire/set answer: the ratified contract does require **set semantics** for `roles`, because it names `Set<ProjectionRole>`. I found no contract line requiring a literal JSON array/set encoding. A boolean object can be semantically isomorphic if the public contract explicitly defines it that way, but absent that, H7 should validate set semantics plus the `fts` / `vector` sub-objects, not invent `searchable_fts` / `searchable_vector` roles.

**P2: PARTLY CONFIRMED.**

Steward is wrong that there is no “ADR-0.8.11 D3”. There is an ADR: [ADR-0.8.11-filter-grammar-unification.md](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/dev/adr/ADR-0.8.11-filter-grammar-unification.md:213). D3 explicitly says no silent fallback/no demotion to post-KNN `json_extract`: [ADR-0.8.11-filter-grammar-unification.md](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/dev/adr/ADR-0.8.11-filter-grammar-unification.md:215), [ADR-0.8.11-filter-grammar-unification.md](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/dev/adr/ADR-0.8.11-filter-grammar-unification.md:225). Code cites the same guarantee: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2191), [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2211).

But Steward is right on the important migration point: reshaping vec0 does **not inherently require re-embedding**. Existing migrations stage persisted vec0 embeddings, drop/recreate `vector_default`, then reinsert the stored blobs: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:12549), [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:12572), [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:12587), and the older reshape stages `vector_default.embedding`: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:12631).

Correction: vectors are **not** persisted in `_fathomdb_vector_rows`; that table is only `{rowid, kind, write_cursor}`: [lib.rs schema](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:176). Actual embeddings are in `vector_default.embedding`: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:12534), inserted by `commit_projection_outcomes`: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:11774).

Code path distinction: `rebuild_vec0()` calls `run_rebuild(false)` then `rebuild_shadow_state`, which truncates vector/readiness rows and replays projectors: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:6775), [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:8008). Those projectors only enqueue vector work: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:13978). Workers then call `embed()` / `embed_batch`: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:11129), [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:10946). So `rebuild_vec0` re-embeds; a purpose-built vec0 reshape migration need not.

**P3: CONFIRMED, with a current-code nuance.**

`strftime('%s', <user value>)` does **not** exist in shipped code. The only `strftime('%s', ...)` hit is `strftime('%s', 'now')` in vector migration code: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:12660). There is user-value `datetime(?1)` in consolidation invalidation, but not the proposed integer conversion via `strftime`: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:4671).

NULL `t_invalid` is absolutely treated as still valid. Schema says `NULL = "still valid"`: [lib.rs schema](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:339). Query filters use `t_invalid IS NULL OR datetime(t_invalid) > datetime('now')`: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:9910), [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:10059), [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:10455). So a proposed conversion that maps malformed invalid-time to SQL NULL would fail open.

`temporal_fallback` is matched by string equality against `substituted_t_valid`: warnings are collected by `kind == "temporal_fallback"` and `substituted_t_valid`, then edge `t_valid` is checked with `fallback_dates.contains(tv)`: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:4253), [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:4434). So the hazard is fail-open coercion plus brittle string equality, not the LLM’s ISO format by itself.
