`strftime('%s', <user value>)` does **not** exist in shipped code. The only `strftime('%s', ...)` hit is `strftime('%s', 'now')` in vector migration code: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:12660). There is user-value `datetime(?1)` in consolidation invalidation, but not the proposed integer conversion via `strftime`: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:4671).

NULL `t_invalid` is absolutely treated as still valid. Schema says `NULL = "still valid"`: [lib.rs schema](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:339). Query filters use `t_invalid IS NULL OR datetime(t_invalid) > datetime('now')`: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:9910), [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:10059), [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:10455). So a proposed conversion that maps malformed invalid-time to SQL NULL would fail open.

`temporal_fallback` is matched by string equality against `substituted_t_valid`: warnings are collected by `kind == "temporal_fallback"` and `substituted_t_valid`, then edge `t_valid` is checked with `fallback_dates.contains(tv)`: [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:4253), [lib.rs](/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/steward-0718/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:4434). So the hazard is fail-open coercion plus brittle string equality, not the LLM’s ISO format by itself.
